reviews.review_text: great quality even if jerry flubs the first verse of brown eyed women, still a kick ass show...quality is great!!   real good!!! { i mean, all these shows have a bit o' hiss} yucky  wait.....on ramble on rose- distortion is here to party on the piano!!!!!yeaaaaa

high fidelity The instruments AND vocals sound particularly crisp and clean to me, unlike alot of shows from this era. Energy level pretty high, but I'm a real sucker for this vintage. One of THE best Casey Jones, and OMSN played as it should be...fast, rockin', no DJG, and lots 'o' Phil. Honorable mention to It Hurts Me Too. It's easy to sometimes take these shows/songs for granted, but if you're into this time period, don't pass on this one. It's a keeper. 5 stars, to average things out a bit.

Why is next night better? The next night's show has many more downloads and reviews, but this show is very good, too.  Some songs sound even better on this recording - vocals louder on T.J. and Truckin', for example.  12/10 fits on 3 discs with lots of extra space - I used the non-repeated songs from 12/09 as filler.  However, 12/09 would make a good download by itself.
What you wanna do... What can you do about it... it's 1971 and this is yet another stellar show!

Holy Cow What a beauty...strong start to finish.  Love the Banter, really makes ya feel like yer there.

Great sound.  Yet another show on my list.

Thankyou both Mr. Kaplan and Mr. Sacks...made my day you have.

Great time Great show, great time. Keith is there; his piano is necessary, imho, for the new songs (Jack, Brown-Eyed, Tennessee, Ramble). But it's better than the preceding three months because Ron's back. And it's better than the following months because, as skwimite noted below, Donna Jean isn't yet there.

That's my story and I'm sticking to it.
- One of the hottest 2nd sets you'll ever hear.

highlight This is my favorite Black Peter ever. Tennessee is solid. That being said, this show is ultra-middling outside of that.
12/10 first set will blow your mind compared to this.
They were probably beat from the Felt Forum shows which explains a kind Peter, run and see.

Get out when the blow! This is a unique time with both Keith and Pigpen in the band.
They spent all of 1971 getting the steam locomotive on the track..
Piggy was feelin’ real good I think he was in heaven hearing Keith back him up while he blew away on the harmonica
